metadata.name: Harmonious Dissonance #19
metadata.description:
'Harmonious Dissonance' combines vertical lines, dots, and noise to evoke a unique visual experience. The canvas comes alive with a dynamic interplay of elements, creating an atmosphere that balances order and chaos.

Vertical lines stand as pillars of structure within the composition. They impart a sense of stability and direction, drawing the viewer's gaze upward and downward, guiding their exploration of the artwork's intricate details.

Amongst these lines are clusters of dots These dots vary in size and density, adding an element of randomness to the piece. From a distance, they create a harmonious texture, while up close, they reveal a fascinating world of individual nuances.

Flecks and fragments of color and texture emerge from the background. The position of lines are adjusted with noise. This noise disrupts the apparent order of the vertical lines and dots, injecting a hint of controlled chaos. 

'Harmonious Dissonance' melds the precision of vertical lines with the spontaneity of dots and the deliberate disorder of noise. It draws viewers into an ever-evolving dialogue between structure and spontaneity, cohesion and disruption.


Created with p5.js.
This was created as part of the GDAP 2023 Summer Class in Taipei.

metadata.name: Distorted Realities #10
metadata.description:
This evocative sketch embarks on a voyage through surreal landscapes, delving into realms where reality blurs and imagination takes flight. Through a fusion of intricate patterns and ethereal hues, this digital creation invites you to traverse the interplay of shifting forms and transient emotions.

Much like a conjured reverie, "Distorted Realities" is a collaborative dance between the artist's vision and the language of code, bringing forth the ineffable into tangible existence. These visuals not only stand as static images but also serve as a bridge between artistry, technology, and the profound exploration of the human psyche. Each stroke is a portal to the unshackled mind, a passage to boundless perception, and an entreaty to uncover the seldom-explored recesses of consciousness.

50 palettes.

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #203
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to “lush, green” and Brut means “dry, raw, or unrefined.”

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growth… but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-Borgström, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
‘S’ : save as png (2376 × 3360)
’V’ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=p’ : paper grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 5940 × 8400 (Chrome only)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append “&g=p&h=t” to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: Poligonal Illusions #12
metadata.description:
Optical art, also known as "Op Art", is an artistic movement that developed mainly in the 1960s. Its main goal is to create optical illusions and visual effects in works of art to stimulate the viewer's visual perception.

To make my contribution to this movement what I fused with the wonders of generative art. I have focused on geometric abstraction using simple shapes such as squares, triangles and straight lines to create repetitive patterns organized in such a way as to cause the desired optical effect.

I have used as a base a common pattern of triangles arranged in a specific way recursively. Finally placed within a general square in such a way that the sum of the areas of the triangles is equal to the area of the container.
As usual, add the "half-finished" drawing effect and a wide variety of color palette.

To download the image in PNG format press [ s ]

Hope you like!
by RosbelDev
